1_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NuclearSpace Vs Global Network.</span><hr size=1> Hormesis experiments seem to defy the reasoning behind it. That any scale rule applies to dosage. Just because 200 degrees will most certainly kill your whole body that doesn't automatically mean 20 degrees will kill 10% of your body. Thankfully Nasa is doing some research into radiation effects. It would be good to have a clearer understanding of what safe maximum dosages are. Current recommended levels are way too low. Ridiculously over exaggerated on the side of caution. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 100<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/1/03 11:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=725.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NuclearSpace Vs Global Network.</span><hr size=1> We know that evidence of harmful effects become observable somewhere in the range of 65 to 165 times the yearly natural background.  This comes from analysis after the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombings.  <br>
